but I know skip guards are prohibited. I need to locate the Java executable in the native image, possibly using GraalVM's `java.home`. `ProcessHandle.current().info().command()` would get the Java path in a JVM, but it's different for a native image. I might create a nested helper main in the test class. Also, do I need to consider the child classpath? In native images, there could be no classpath, which complicates things a bit.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native test classes**\\n\\nI'm thinking about what happens if the native image doesn't have test classes on the filesystem. It might, but I can't rely on that. Maybe I should check what `java.class.path` contains; it might include build/classes. To simplify things, a child code could be a one-liner source launched via `java` in source-file mode. I could write a temporary Java file, `TerminalUtilsConsoleProbe.java`, import TerminalUtils, and then compile and run it. But I wonder if I can locate the library on the classpath in a native test.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_asusV2M79RpkE4MOvYKgxrRZ|fc_0f424351e26f56d20169f3d8b76b0c819cacbd38861d930993", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "java -version 2>&1 | head -5"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"java -version 2>&1 | head -5\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2186, "output": 1261, "cacheRead": 15872, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 19319, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777588387464, "responseId": "resp_0f424351e26f56d20169f3d8a40194819ca5e7599e84040c98"}}
